This paper is primarily focused on artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) techniques for game-playing agents. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.AI. The paper also discusses the use of information theory to select a subset of problems, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper analyzes correlations between scores and win-rates, which could be considered a form of statistical inference (cs.ST). The paper also discusses the General Video Game AI (GVGAI) framework, which could be classified under the category of computer graphics (cs.GR). Finally, the paper discusses the dimensions of effective variance in game design, which could be classified under the category of game theory (cs.GT) or social and information networks (cs.SI).
